body:
### Version

Yosys 0.43 (git sha1 ead4718e5, clang++ 14.0.0-1ubuntu1.1 -fPIC -Os)

### On which OS did this happen?

Linux

### Reproduction Steps

Given the following VHDL design (`wrong_src.vhdl`)
```
library ieee;
use ieee.std_logic_1164.all;
use ieee.std_logic_unsigned.all;

entity work is
   port (
      clk        : in std_logic;
      reset_in   : in std_logic;
      reset_out  : out std_logic_vector(3 downto 0)
   );
end work;

architecture behavior of work is
   signal reset_reg : std_logic_vector(3 downto 0);
begin

   reset_out <= reset_reg;

   intr_proc: process(clk, reset_in, reset_reg)
   begin
      if reset_in = '1' then
         reset_reg <= (others => '0');
      elsif rising_edge(clk) then
         if reset_reg /= "1111" then
            reset_reg <= reset_reg + "0001";
         end if;
      end if;
   end process;

end behavior;
```

The src attribute of the $add cell corresponding to `reset_reg <= reset_reg + "0001";` is:
```
attribute \src "../vhdl_packages/vhdl_2019/src/ieee/syn_arit.vhd:838.41-838.65"
cell $add $verific$add_7$../vhdl_packages/vhdl_2019/src/ieee/syn_arit.vhd:838$14
```

If I add a integer literal instead of a binary literal, i.e, substituting
`reset_reg <= reset_reg + "0001";`
for 
`reset_reg <= reset_reg + 1;`

like in the following design (correct_src.vhdl):

```
library ieee;
use ieee.std_logic_1164.all;
use ieee.std_logic_unsigned.all;

entity work is
   port (
      clk        : in std_logic;
      reset_in   : in std_logic;
      reset_out  : out std_logic_vector(3 downto 0)
   );
end work;

architecture behavior of work is
   signal reset_reg : std_logic_vector(3 downto 0);
begin
  
   reset_out <= reset_reg;

   intr_proc: process(clk, reset_in, reset_reg)
   begin
      if reset_in = '1' then
         reset_reg <= (others => '0');
      elsif rising_edge(clk) then
         if reset_reg /= "1111" then
            reset_reg <= reset_reg + 1;
         end if;
      end if;
   end process;

end behavior;
```
The src attribute is correct:
```
attribute \src "correct_src.vhdl:25.26-25.35"
cell $add $verific$add_7$correct_src.vhdl:25$13
```

Note that wrong_src.vhdl and correct_src.vhdl are equivalent, proved with the following eqy script.

```
[gold]
verific -vhdl2019 correct_src.vhdl
verific -import work
prep -top work

[gate]
verific -vhdl2019 wrong_src.vhdl
verific -import work
prep -top work

[strategy simple]
use sat
depth 10
```

# Note:
This issue comes from processing a bigger project, and it was reduced for easier debugging.
If we remove this in both designs:
```
if reset_in = '1' then
         reset_reg <= (others => '0');
```
The designs are no longer equivalent.


### Expected Behavior

The src attribute of the $add cell points to the user design:
```
attribute \src "wrong_src.vhdl:25.26-25.35"
cell $add $verific$add_7$wrong_src.vhdl:25$13
```

### Actual Behavior

The src attribute of the $add cell points to the library where addition operator is implemented:
```
attribute \src "../vhdl_packages/vhdl_2019/src/ieee/syn_arit.vhd:838.41-838.65"
cell $add $verific$add_7$../vhdl_packages/vhdl_2019/src/ieee/syn_arit.vhd:838$14
```

